{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_janeway_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150874/1930101101/0527.xml":{"full_text":"Welcome Sons of -Notre Dame and Uncle Sam\u2019s Midshipmen\n40 PAGES\nTHE WEATHER\nSooth Bead and Vicinity\nFair with Fresh Winds\nl> VOL XLVII, NO. 284*\n*_. 9\nSOUTH BEND. INDIANA, SATURDAY, OCTOBER II, 1930 s'f\n-f\ni Hi i i mmm\nTtfO PARTS\u2014PART ONE\n1\nPRICE THREE CENTS\nJURYMEN RETURN\nMURDER CHARGES\nIN CHILD'S DEATH\nt Court Appoints Attorney\nfor Confessed Slayer of,\nMarverine Apple.\nGeorge Sherman Myers, Indicted\nr* for the rape and slaying of niue\nyear-old Marverine Apple, pleaded\nnot guilty to a charge of first degree\nmurder when arraigned before Cir\nsuit Judge Cyrus E. Pattee Friday.\nThe Indictment charging him with\nthe murder of the child was returned\nearlier in the morning by the Circuit\ncourt grand'Jury.\nBy previous arrangement Sheriff\nThomas' A. Goodrich and his deputy,\nWillis Sriver hurried to Michigan\nCity with a release order from the\nCircuit judge to bring Myers here for\narraignment.\nEdwin Sommerer, county poor at\ntorney, was appointed by the court to\nact as defense counsel for Myers.\nMyers was allowed to stay in the\ncounty Jail for a short time to con\nfer with Sommerer. He was then re\nturned to Michigan City.\nOther Indictments\nHie Myers Indictment was one of\nfive returned by the grand Jury.\nThe list Included a first degree\nmurder indictment against Herbert\nSmith for the slaying of his wife,\nLula Smith, two weeks ago. and one\nagainst Clyde Fitzgerald, /charging\nhim with assault and battery to rape\nand kill and with being an habitual\ncriminal.\nThe true bids also Include indict\nments against Mrs. Myrtle Hilda\nbridle for receiving stolen goods, Mrs.\nStanley Ladd and Mrs. Iva Greer for\ngrand larceny and robbery with a\nweapon.\nThe three were linked with the\n1 Joyal-Ladd-Hildabridle filling station,\nbanditry case. The fifth indictment,\ninvolving a $40,000 forgery, was kept\nsecret by the prosecutor.\nArraign Many\nImmediately after, the return of\nthe grand Jury and while waiting for\nthe arrival of Myers, Judge Pattee\nand Prosecutor Harry S. Taylor held\narraignment for nearly a score of\nprisoners waiting trial in the county\njail.\nThe arraignment list includes the'\nfollowing:\nLucien Winlcki, vehicle taking, not\nguilty.\nEdward Slisz, larceny, guilty.\nDale Goshorn, burglary, dot guilty.\nHoward Douglass, burglary, jpt\nguilty. f\nHarry Holt, assault and battery\nwith intent to kill, ndt guilty.'\nClyde Fitzgerald, not guilty on all\ncounts.\nJ. C. Seanor, worthless check, not\nguilty.\nMrs. Myrtle Hildabridle, receiving\nstolen goods, ndt guilty.\nMrs. Stanley Ladd .larceny and rob\nbery with a gun, guilty.\nMrs. Iva Greer, larceny and rob\nbery with a gun, guilty.\nMrs. Edith Bennett, larceny, guilty.\nMISSING CONSTABLE\nIS BELIEVED SLAIN\nBy International Smi Service:\nLAFAYETTE, Iud., Oct. 10.\u2014Con?\nstable Harry Kendall, 75, who had\nbeen working at the office of Justice\nof Peace James H. Porter has been\nmissing since Oct. 2, according to a\ni eport made to police here today. Of\nficers working on the case expressed\nthe fear that Kendall met with foul\nplay. He was last seen walking to\n1 ward the Wabash river.\nYOUTH IS SENTENCED\nFOR THEFT OF BAG!\nBy fnlted Press:\nINDIANAPOLIS, Oct 10.\u2014A one to\n10 year sentence in the Indiana\nstate reformatory was given James\nSmiles, 23, Indianapolis, upon convic\ntion of a charge of stealing a travel-'\ning bag containing toilet articles and\nwearing apparel belonging to Miss\nJean Bucklin, Brazil, from the state\nsenate chamber, last August.\nSmiles admitted previous convic\ntions on similar charges.\nIndiana\u2014Fair Saturday; not much\nchange In tempera tore.\ni/ower Michigan\u2014Partly cloudy, pos\nsibly light showers Saturday north\nportion; not much change in temper\nature.\nI,ocal atmospheric conditions for the\nnext 34 hours as indicated by The\n.Vows-Times barometer:\nFair weather with fresh winds.\nThe fallowing temperatures were re\ncorded by The News-Time* thermom\neter from it o\u2019clock Thursday night to\n9 o'clock rtlday night:\n9 p. m.63\n10 p. m. ..64\n11 p. m. .64\nMidnight '..83\n1 a. m. .(11\n3 a. m.81\n3 a. m. ..61\n4 a. m.\u00abS0\n3 a. m.59\n0 a. m.\u00ab....V\n7 a. ra.\u00bb.CO\n5 a. m.65\na a. m. ..*o\n10 a. m. .......74\n11 a. in. ..78\n12 Noon \u201e\u00bb....76\n1 p. m. .78\nS p. w.\n3 p. m.\n4 p. m.\n5 p. m.\n..78\n..78\n..77\n.74\n8 p. m. ........71\n7 p. m.\n8 p. ni.\np. m.\n....69\n....OH\nh\nBrazil Marine\nForces Yield\nTo Rebel Band\nBy FERNANDO CALDAS,\n.United Press Staff Correspondent.\nPORTO ALEGRE, RIO GRANDE\nDo SUL, Brazil, Oct. 10.\u2014The fed\neral government\u2019s marine forces de\nfending Jolnville, in the state of\nSanta Catharina, surrendered today\nafter a violent battle with revolu\ntionary forces.\nThe captain and a lieutenant of\nthe federal forces vfere taken prison\ners and the revolutionaries began ad\nvancing along the coast of the state\nin a general offensive which the\nsouthern rebel armies have launched\nagainst the state of Sao Paulo,\nJoinville is in the northern part of\nSanta Catharina, near the coast and\nnear the Parana border.\nRevolutionary fprces inarched on\nthe federal army headquarters, open\ning an intense fire which lasted for\n10 minutes. Machine guns were used.\nRebels then attacked the war ar\nsenal, where resistance was weak,\nbut there was severe fighting. The\nnumber of dead was not definitely\nestablished. Government troops re\nsisted stubbornly throughout the eve\nning and there was widespread fight\ning in the outlying districts, where\nrifle fire and hand grenades cleared\nthe streets.\nRevolutionary forces totalling about\n40,000 men were reported advancing\nfrom the state of Parana into Sao\nPaulo today, in an effort to take pos\n(Continued on page 4, column 2)\nOFFER TRIBUTE\nTO R-JOTOERO\n\u201cThe Last Post\u201d Sounded\nFor Crash Victims\nin London,\nBjr United Press:\nLONDON, Oct. 10.\u2014Great Britain\u2019s\ntribute to the dead of the R-101 dis\naster was /paid Friday at the me\nmorial service at St. Paul\u2019s cathedral\nmarking the most solemn day of\nmourning since the World war.\nThe Prince of Wales, representing\nthe. king, and the Duke of York stood\nwith relatives of the victims of the\ndisaster and diplomats of world pow\ners as royal air force trumpeters\nsounded \u201cthe last post,\u201d to conclude\nthe service.\nBy United Press:\nBEAUVAIS, France, Oct. 10.\u2014\nWorkmen scrapping the wreckage of\nthe R-101 near Allonne Friday found\ntwo of the five motors of the big sl\\ip\nintact.\nMISHAWAKA MAN\nDIES UNDER TRAIN\nV\nHammond Wilson Killed\nAt Pine Street Rail\nroad Crossing.\nHammond Wilson, 81, of 311 E.\nSixth street, Mishawaka,* was in\nstantly killed shortly after 5 o\u2019clock\nFriday afternoon, when be was struck\nby a fast west bound New York Cen\ntral passenger train at Pine street\nand the New York Central tracks.\nAccording to Lawrence Ransbergtr,\n18, of 427 E. Fourth street, an eye\nwitness of the accident, Wilsap. was\nwalking along the side of the tracks\n\u00abd when he noticed the Approaching\ntin turned and walked or fell di\nrectly into the path of the trhin.\nCoroner Called\nWilson was employed at the Dodge\nManufacturing Co. of Mishawaka as\na sweeper, and made his residence at\nthe home of his daughter, Miss Mary\nWilson, who could not be reached at\nthe time of the fatal accident'\nCoroner C. B. Crumpacker was im\nmediately called to the scene of the\naccident but will not give a verdict\nuntil a further investigatiton has been\nmade.\nThe passenger train Was in charge\nof Engineer J. 3. Haeffer, Fireman K.\nStrong and Conducton\u2019R. Bully.\n\u2018RAIN BABY\u2019 MOTHER\nLOSES COURT TIGHT\nBy United Promt\nBLOOMINGTON, Ind., Oct I\nMrs. Marie Breedlove, Bloomington,\nmother of the Indianapolis \"rain\nbaby\u201d, lost her court fight for sup\nport money for the child from Wil\nliam Breedlove, her former husband.\nThe child, Robot Eugene Breed\nlove, was bom after the couple was\ndivorced. At the time of the divorce,\nJudge Herbert A. Rqndell, in Mon\nroe Circuit court, ordered Breedlove\nto contribute tr the support of an\nolder son, Vernon Lee Breedlove, al\nthough the husband charged his wife\ntold him he was not the child\u2019s\ni lather.\n1 t 1 s\nt\nAMERICAN PLANE\nCROSSES OCEAN\nFOR SECOND TIME\nColumbia Makes Forced\nLanding Near Cornish\nCoast.\nBy United Press:\nST. MARYS, Scilly Islanli. Oct. 10.\n\u2014The airplane Columbia, piloted by\nCaptain J Errol Boyd and Lieutenant*\nHarry P. Connor, ended its second\neastward crossing of the north At\nlantic wean today on a rot ky. beach\nat the islet of Tresco\u2014some 28 miles\nshort of the Cornish cease.\nThe plane was reported undamaged\nin the traced landing on the beach.\nThe Columbia was driven some 150\nmiles off her course from Harbor\nGrace, Newfoundland, to Croydon\nairdrome, near London, before .the\nlanding cn the Tresco beach.\nHope to Continue 1\nTresco Isle is one of the toughest\nparts of the southwest coasl of Eng\nland, out it was said the fliers hoped\nto continue their flight to Croydon,\nperhaps tomorrow.\nCroydon airdrome authorities were\nnotified by telegraph of the landing\nof the Columbia.\nThis was the second forced landing\nin the Columbia\u2019s transatlantic his\ntory. In 1927, Clarence Chamberlin\nand Charles A. Levine flew from\nRooseveit fleldv to Germany in the\nship, t)ut were'forced down short of\ntheir objective\u2014Berlin.\nThe Columbia was the flist plane\nto make the transatlantic flight\ntwice, and its record was more re\nmarkable because of the f&rft that the\nsingle engine had not been changed\nsince Chamberlin and Levine flew to\nGermany three years ago.\nThe veteran monoplane Columbia\nleft Harbor Grace at 10:20 yesterday\nmorning, scheduled to strike a course\nsouth of Ireland on her second flight\nfrom America to Europe. The fliers\nexpected to make the flight in about\n24 hours, which would make the ship\nclose to scheduled time.\nThe weather conditions off the Irish\ncoast continued favorable with a tail,\nwind speeding the plane on toward\nits goal in England.\nSince Boyd and Connor Carried no\nradio equipment, the only word of\ntheir progress necessarily came from\nthe few ships along their route. The\nsteamer Lancastria reported sighting\n(Continued bn page 4, column 1.)\nFESS IS REELECTED\n-MEMORIAL LEADER\nBy United Press:\nSPRINGFIELD, O., Oct.. 19.\nUnited States Senator Simeon D. Fess\nof Ohio, was re-elected' chairman of\nthe George -Rogers Clark National\nMemorial commission at the annual\nmeeting here incident to the Spring\nfield sesqui-centennial celebration\ncommemorating the battle of Piqua\nand the new Clark State* park. Other\nofficers elected with D. Frank Cul\nbertson, Indianapolis, vice chairman;\nRalph Gilbert,-Shelbyville, Ind., legal\nsecretary, and C. D. Coleman, Indian\napolis, executive secretary. The cele\nbration, which was attended by Vice\nPresident Charles Curtis, and other\nnotables, ends tomorrow.\nPOISON ALCOHOL\nKILLS WAR VET\n-4 f f:\nProbe Boston Bootleg\nConditions Following,\nt Four Deaths,\nBy HENRY MINOTT,\nUnited' Press Staff Correspondent.\nBOSTON, Oct. 10. Discussion ot\nbootleg conditions in Boston durtng\nthe American Legion convention was\nintensified today by reports that\npoison liquor resulted in, two deaths\nand sent at least 358 persons to hos\npitals while the Legion was in ses\nsion.\nSome 300 other liquor victims were\nreported to have been treated in the\nout-patient departments of hospitals\nand at first aid stations.\nDisabled Vet Dies.\nPoison alcohol was held responsible\nfor the deaths of Charles Henry. 48\nyear-old disabled World war veteran,\nand his wife Mildred. Two other\ndeaths resulted from skull fractures\n\"suffered while the victims were in\ntoxicated.\nHospital authorities reported that\nmost of those treated -.ere not\nLegionnaires but were merely posing\nas members of the organization.\nPaul E. Leary, Little Palls. N. Y*\nLegionnaire was fined $250 in fed\neral court on a bootleg charge after\nfederal agents claimed to have found\n100 quarts of liquor in his possession\nat the Copley-Plaza hotel. He was\nthe only Legionnaire arrested on\nbootleg charges during the conven\nMIDDIES ARRIVE TO BATTLE N. D.\ng\niiiifiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiili\nmm\nr Km\niii \u25a0\u2022inafflax\nNews-Times Photo.\nThey'll dedicate the new stadium at Notre Dame today\u2014-this group ,of young: midshipmen\u2014pictured here as they descended from the train at\nLapaz Friday mhrnlng. Forty-four -niddies, with Coach Dill Ingram, himself a former student at the academy, are in the group, photographed by the\nNews-Times cameraman. Coach Ingram, -in civilian clothes in the middle of the picture, predicts his squad will prove formidable to the hopes of thb\nIrish in dedicating the stadium with victory. x.\nRALLY IN STOCKS\nENDS LOWPRICES\nImpressive Recovery Is\nStaged by Leaders\non Market.\nPy ELMER C. WALZER,\nUnited Press Financial Editor.\nNEW YORK, Oct'. 10.\u2014The stock\nmarket made an impressive showing\nFriday when, after breaking into new\nf lows for many leaders since 1928, a\nrally set in which took many above\nthe close yesterday.\nToday's was the first spirited re\ncovery in the past month, during\nwhich time prices have sagged gent\nly with United States Steel breaking\nthrough its 1929 resistance level of\n150.\nSteel again Friday was the leader.\nThe decline this morning, which saw\nsteel going to its low since 1928, was\nled by the premier blue chip.\nThe rally thisv afternoon also was\nled by steel. At its low Friday steel\nwas at 144%. In the last few min\nutes of trading it had come back to\n149 after a close of 146 yesterday.\nStocks Rise.\nAmerican Telephone, another lead\ner, turned about after making a low\nsince, 1928 at 192% and near the close\nwas at 200 up 3 from Thursday.\nCorresponding rallies were noted\nthrough most of the list including\nCase, American Can, Westinghouse\nElectric, Bethlehem Steel, Vanadium,\nGeneral Electric and a long list of\nspecial issues.\nThe market closed irregularly high\ner but a few weak spots remained\nsuch as Dunhill, Electric Auto-Lite,\nGeneral Theaters Equipment, Fox\nand Loew\u2019s.\nWith the turn in stocks wheat\nsnapped back and closed with gains\nof more than 2 cents. Cotton ral\nlied smartly whilp. bonds turned up\n\u201eward,\nUnited States Steel closed on the\nhigh of the hay at 149%, up 3%\npionts /from the previous close and 5\npoints above thf low. American Tele\nphone closed at 199%, up 2% from\nthe previous close; American Can\n118%, up 4% and J. E. Case 127, up 5.\n\\nvff Tiekets.,.antl a\nFootball Dope Book!\nA feyrmore 'hours and\nI Notre Daitt^ and N&v>\nI will be facing each other\nin thrilling, colorful\ngame in die new stadium.\nJust before die kick-off\ndie Dedication ceremon\niet will have taken place\nbefore notables from all\nover the country.\nAre >ou going to be one\nof (he 55,000 people who\nwill witness this memor-'\nable event? Have you\nsecured your seats? ;v:^\nFor the convenience of its\nleaders, The News-Times\nFete to Honor O'Leary Cow\nIs Dubbed Political Move\nWill Rogers Says\u2014\nBEVERLY BOLLS, Calif., Oct\n9.\u2014If It Ain\u2019t one Calamity hits\nns its another. Did yon read where\nJessie Livermore, E. F. Hatton,\nMarshall Field, Frelinghuysen,,\nSloan of General Motors, and Far\nrell of V. S. Steel, and a host of\nothers, have been buying their\n\u201cantique\u201d furniture In England\nbefore it was even aged in the\nwood. They couldn\u2019t make these\nnew antique, \u201chigh boys\u201d fast\nenough' for our new rich \"old\nboys.\u201d\nThis expose will bring a hard\nship on our wealthy. It\u2019s liable to\nforce \u2019em to use American made\nfurniture.\nUs middle class over here never\nhave to worry about having old\nfurniture to point out to our\nfriends, we buy it on payments\nand before it\u2019s paid for, it\u2019s plenty\nantique.\nYours,\nWILL ROGERS.\nARMY DESERTER\nKILLEDJNHOLBUP\nCompanion Is Captured\nAfter Chase Through\nOhio City.\nJ\nBy United Preg\u00a7:\nCINCINNATI, O., Oct. 10.\u2014Earl\nMartin, 21, Sterans, Ky., who deserted\nfrom the army at Fort 'Benjamin\nHarrison, Indianapolis, last Monday,\nwas shot to'death in an attempted\nfilling station holdup here today. His\ncompanion, Charles Stanton, 24,\nUnion City, Ind., was captured.\nMartin was killed by Motorcycle\nOfficer Harry Holtman who arrived\nat the station as the robbery was in\nprogress.\noffer* ^limited number of\nseats for this big game.\nThey will be on sale until\n11 o\u2019clock Saturday\nmorning at the regular\nprice of $5 at die Classi\nfied Counter in The News\nTunes budding.\nA Football Dqpe Book,\nlisting 170 college teams\nand their records, rules\ngoverning the game, score\nsheets and the Rockne\nWarner-Jones All-Ameri\nca selections^ is yours for\nthe asking!\nI Hearst, Thompson Cast\nBouquets Copiously at\nCelebration.\nBy United Fran\nCHICAGO,' Oct. 10.\u2014A celebration\nthat Mayor William Hale Thompson,\nthe \u201cBig Bill\u201d of Chicago politics,\nsponsored at Soldier field in com\nmemoration of victory over the great\nfire of Oct. 9, 1871, found the cityjs\npress sharply divided today in its\nanalyses of Thompson\u2019s motives.\nThe Tribune and the Daily News\naccepted the celebration as marking\nthe start of a campaign by the mayor\nfor reelectlon to a fourth term, an\nevent which the news said would be\nan even greater catastrophe than the\nfire.\nHearst Honor Guest\nThe Hearst publications, On the\nother hand, hailed it as a \u201cpatriotic\nupheaval,\u201d and \u201cthe greatest and\nI most impressive demonstration in the\nhistory of the city.\u201d William Ran\ndolph Hearst was the guest of honor\nat the celebration.\nThompson himself described the\ncelebration as \u2018'the biggest show Bill\nThompson ever put Over.\u201d\nIt was estimated that about 50,000\npersons took part in the parade and\ndemonstration. The Tribune said this\nnumber probably was disappointing\nto close observers of the mayor\u2019s poli\ntical fortunes and indicated a belief\nmost of those present were police or\nmembers of the various bands, cal\nvary units and other organizations\nactually participating'. The throng\nless than half filled the stadium.\nBouquets in Affluence\nHearst, as the principal speaker,\nspoke of Thompson as \u201cthe greatest\nmayor Chicago ever had\u201d and\nThompson returned the compliment\nby calling Hearst \u201cthe greatest liv\ning American.\u201d\nThe \u25a0'occasion was the signal for\nmuch editorializing by the various\npapers.\nSaid the Daily News:\n\u201cThe Chicago fire of Oct. 9, 1871,\nwa$, of course, a great calamity to\nthis city^ A greater calamity, how\never, has been, all things considered,\nthe three terms of William Hale\nThompson as mayor of Chicago. With\nthat fact in mind.one may be tempt\ned to concede the appropriateness of\nthe choice of the anniversary of the\ngreat fire for the inauguration of Mr.\nThompson\u2019s fourth campaign for the\nmayoralty.\u201d\nThe Tribune said:\n\u201cThe only competition today\u2019s big\nshow will have is offered by the\nwhale on the old soap factory lot\n(an embalmed whale on exhibition.)\nThe citizenry* may take its choice.\nThe only advantage the whale has\nas a show is that it is protectively\npickled and might be preferred by\nany one sensitive that way.\u201d\nSaid the Herald-Examiner, Hearst\npaper, of the celebration:\n\u201cIt sounded a great promise for\nthe future, it renewed faith in the\nquick return of prosperity, and it re\ninspired the citizens of Chicago with\nthe spirit of .American patriotism.\u201d\nDOMESTIC BATTLE\nBLAMED IN SUICIDE\nBy United Pkmi\nGARY, Ind., Oct. 10.\u2014A domestic\nquarrel was blamed fur the suicide\nFriday of Peter Muslin, 47, Gary\nsteel mill employe, who drank a half\npint of muriatic acid.\nMuslin/ father of 15 children, was\nsaid to have quarreled with his wife\nconcerning a sop who had just re\nturned from the state reformatory.\nBANDIT SUSPECT\nEVADESJAPTURE\nMuncie Jail Breaker Is\ns Named in Indiana\nBank Holdups^\nBy United Press:\nMUNCIE, Did., Oct. 10.\u2014Search for\nJoel Stamper, 22, who escaped from\njail here a few days ago, was inten\nsified today with reports of investiga\ntors that officials in two banks had\nidentified him as one of the men who\nrobbed those Institutions.\nIdentify Photographs\nAuthorities said that Stamper has\nbeen identified by photographs as a\nparticipant in the Liberty Center\nState bank holdup on April 25, 1930,\nin which $hS00 was taken; and the\nTwelve Mile bank, near Rochester, In\nAugust. His wife, who is now held\nin jail in Logansport, was identified\nas- accompanying the Twelve Mile\nrobbers, police said.\nLogansport authorities have indi\ncated their intention of filing charges\nagainst Mrs. Stamper.\nAUTOIST IS INJURED\nAS CAR HITS POLE\nStanley Mikolajczak, 56, 1521 W.\nDunham street,, was in St. Joseph\nhospital, suffering from two broken\nlegs following an automobile crash\nlate Friday afternoon.\nMikolajczak was riding in a truck\nwith John Doorsky, when the latter\nlost control of the steering wheel.\nThe truck careened to the side of the j\nroad and crashed into a telephone\npole in the 1900 block, on Ford street.\nBRITISH INDUSTRY\nSEEKS U. S. HELP\nEnglish Steel Men Are\nStudying Replogle\nPlan.\nBy International New. Service:\nLONDON, Oct. 16.\u2014Jacob Leonard\nReplogle* American steel magnate, is\nto reorganize the steel Industry of\nBritain, according to reports current\nin the city of London.\nGreat strides have been made in\nrecent years in the modernization of\nsteel works in Britain. The produc\ntive capacity of the Industry has been\nincreased by over 50 per cent, while,\nat .the same time, the. number of\nworkers needed has been reduced.\nInvite Replogle\nBut even this advance has not been\nsufficient to enable-Britain to com\npete successfully in the world\u2019s mar\nkets, and, accordingly, 12 months ago,\nReplogle, who was the United States\nSteel administrator during the war,\nwas invited by British manufacturers\nto draw up plans for re-organising, the\nIndustry.\nHis ideas are now before British j\nfinanciers. Involved we the replace- j\nment of the majority of British Mast j\nfurnaces, with an average capacity of i\nabout 120-150 tons a day, by modem]\nfurnaces with a 1,000 tons of daily ca\npacity. The plan includes the setting\nup of great modem coke ovens, com\nplete with by-product recovery plant.\nThese ovens, it is estimated, would\nsave $3.50 to $4.00 a ton of coke per j\nTEAMS PREPARE\nFOR EPIC GAME\nAT NEWSTADIUM\nFather O\u2019Donnell, Rftcknc\nand Admiral Robison\nV on Program..\nSALIENT FACTS\nIN' NAVY GAME\nNotre Dame-Navy fame kkkofT\nat t o\u2019clock Saturday afternoon.\nAttendance 55,000.\nDedication speech by Frank E.\nBering at 1:45 o\u2019clock.\nAfter 43 years in college football,\nplaying a star role in the develop\nment of a game that involves millions\nof dollars and millions of spectators,\nNotre Dame Friday night welcomed its\nalumni, guests and friends to the\nformal dedication of its new football\nstadium.\nBehind the high green fex?ce which\nsurrounds old Cartier held, with\nstudent managers posted at vantage\npoints tc ward off the curious, the\nNotre Dame and Navy teams went\nthrough their final drill Friday after\nnoon for the game that will dedicate\nthe stadium Saturday.\nHie Irish took the field early for\ntheir practice on the attack that may\nprove the downfall of the Navy, just\nas their playing 'brought victory in\nthe last meeting of the two a year\nago in Baltimore. Later m the after\nnoon Coach Ingram brought out his\nsquad and tjhe Notre Danie players\nwithdrew to. the fleldhouse.\nNavy Expresses Confidence\nConfidence reigned in the Navy\ngroup loi\u2019jwi v a victory last Satur\nday in W $\u00abning game, and the\nnews that Notre Dame\u2019s squad will,\nbe weakened by the loss of three\nVeterans. Yet Rockne apparently is\nunmoved over the prospect of Mill-\nJins, Donoghue and Leahy out of the\nlineup.\ntf Navy brings out a passing at\ntack, the Irish are going' to be pre\npared, for there have been daily\nworkouts on defense. Big Joe Savoldi\nis slated to fill Mullins' berth and the\nNavy recalls his work last year.\nThe squad of midshipmen, accom\npanied by high officials of the aca\ndemy, was greeted by a group of sev\neral hundred w\u2019hen it arrived this\nmorning at Lapaz, and tnen brought\nto the South Bend Country club\nwhere headquarters fpr the visitors\nhave been arranged.\nFor those whose associations with\nthe university have brought them\nclose to the traditions of Notre Dame,\nthe festivities on the eve of the dedi\ncation game with the Navy football\nteam, have some singular meaning.\nTo the greater throng it will\u2019be an-\nother spectacle in college football, set\napart from other games only because\n(Continued on page 4, column 1)\nTHUGS GET COLD\nFEET;LEAVE LOOT\nHand cuf f Ban k Em*\nployes; Flee When\nNerve Falters.\n\nB,r International Mewl Service:\nNEW YORK, Oct. 10.\u2014Two bandits.\nlost their nerve today and fled when\na rich haul was within their grasp\nafter they had held up and hand\ncuffed the employes of a Brooklyn\nbank.\nOne. by one the bandits had met\nthe bank employes as they entered\nthe building and then^ with all of\nthem handcuffed In the cellar and an\nhour to work before the bank was\ndue to open, they fled. t\nEdward Ling, night watchman of\nthe bank, heard the side door Bell,\nring at 7:30 a. m.\nPoses as Messenger\nHe went to the door and saw a,\nman dressed in a messenger\u2019s uni\nform.\nLing, thinking the man was de\nlivering a telegram, opened the door\nand put out his hand to receive It.\nInstead he received a suddenly-pro\nduced pistol which was thrust against\nhis stomach. 4\n\u201cGet back into the bank,\" the\n\u201cmessenger\u201d ordered. Ling obeyed\nan^ at the same moment, a second\nman who had been hidden from his\nsight Joined the \u201cmessenger.\u201d\nToday\u2019s Index\nPage Section\nEditorials 6 1\nSociety .8 1\nRadio 2 2\nHeart Hungry I 2\nAmusements 2 2 ,t\nSports i.. 4-5-6 2 5\nState x 7 2\nMishawaka ..,.14-15 2\nComic Pages ..16-17 2\nMarkets 8\u2019 r2\nClassified Ads .18^19 2","height":"32488","width":"23904"}}
